items.abstract: <jats:p>The performance of Pd electrocatalysts for formic acid electrooxidation was improved by application of metal oxide-multiwall carbon nanotubes composites as a catalyst support. Hybrid oxides/MWCNTs were synthesized by two different methods: chemical reduction method and impregnation method. Pd based catalysts were synthesized by polyol method on the MWCNTs or oxide/MWCNTs composites. The In<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> was deposited on MWCNTs by impregnation method (In<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>/MWCNTs-IM support) and in the presence of NaBH<jats:sub>4</jats:sub> (In<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>/MWCNTs-NaBH<jats:sub>4</jats:sub> support). The physical properties of the Pd/In<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>/MWCNTs-IM, Pd/In<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>/MWCNTs-NaBH<jats:sub>4</jats:sub>, Pd/SnO<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>/MWCNTs, and Pd/MWCNTs catalysts were characterized and their electrocatalytical performance in formic acid oxidation was compared. During Pd deposition on In<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>/MWCNTs-NaBH<jats:sub>4</jats:sub> support, InPd<jats:sub>2</jats:sub> structure was formed as observed by XRD. The electrochemical tests indicate that the two Pd/ In<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>/MWCNTs electrocatalysts have higher electrocatalytic activity than those of Pd/SnO<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>/MWCNTs and Pd/MWCNTs. The best performance was observed for the catalyst obtained by In<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> impregnation of MWCNTs denoted by Pd/In<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>/MWCNTs-IM.</jats:p>
title: Synthesis and Electrocatalytical Application of Hybrid Pd/Metal Oxides/MWCNTs

items.abstract:
<jats:title>Summary</jats:title>
				<jats:p>In 2010 - 2011 the influence of beeswax foundation adulterated with different percentages of paraffin, on comb construction, brood rearing and bee colonies development was evaluated. Beeswax foundation adulterated with different rate of paraffin (10%, 30%, 50%) was prepared. Each year of the study into 7 experimental bee colonies set in Dadant type bee-hives, the three-frames queen insulators were inserted. Every frame in the insulators had a half of the foundation made from pure beeswax (the control - 0% paraffin) and a second half made from wax adulterated with paraffin (experimental). As a result every colony had an insulator with 3 frames with beeswax foundation with different percentages of paraffin (10 and 0%, 30 and 0%, 50 and 0%). The queens were put in the insulators what stimulated bees to prepare a place for laying eggs, thus, to construct the combs on the foundation.</jats:p>
				<jats:p>Paraffin used in our experiment had no negative impact on the bee colonies. Bees drew out the foundation properly, and no destruction was observed. The queens laid eggs on the systematically drawn out comb cells. Brood development was normal and its quality was suitable. The worker bees emerged after 21 days. No case of brood or emerging worker bees death was noted.</jats:p>
				<jats:p>Because of the different chemical compositions and purities of the paraffin available on the domestic market, it is impossible to exclude the fact that such paraffin may cause harmful effects on bee colonies.</jats:p>
title: Comb Construction and Brood Development on Beeswax Foundation Adulterated with Paraffin
